# Why Women Are Paid Less Than Men: An In-Depth Analysis

## Introduction

The gender pay gap, the difference in earnings between women and men, remains a persistent and complex issue worldwide. Despite decades of progress in education and workforce participation, women continue to earn less than men on average. This report aims to provide a comprehensive, evidence-based analysis of why women are paid less than men, drawing on recent and reliable research. It will explore factors such as occupational sorting, motherhood penalties, discrimination, and societal norms, and will critically evaluate the extent to which these factors contribute to the wage gap.

---

## Overview of the Gender Pay Gap

On average, women earn approximately 77 to 80 cents for every dollar earned by men in the United States and similar figures are observed in other developed countries ([Eberhard, 2014](https://medium.com/@kristin.eberhard/why-do-women-get-paid-less-than-men-3e9f4e9e1b3b); [Economist, 2022](https://www.economist.com/briefing/2022/01/13/why-are-women-paid-less-than-men)). This gap persists even after accounting for education, experience, and job type, indicating that the causes are multifaceted and not solely explained by differences in qualifications or hours worked.

---

## Key Factors Contributing to the Gender Pay Gap

### 1. Occupational Sorting and Career Choices

Women and men tend to work in different occupations, with women disproportionately represented in lower-paying fields such as education, healthcare, and administrative roles, while men dominate higher-paying sectors like engineering, technology, and finance. This phenomenon, known as occupational sorting, accounts for a significant portion of the pay gap.

However, occupational sorting itself is influenced by societal norms, gender stereotypes, and early educational experiences. Girls often receive less encouragement to pursue STEM (Science, Technology, Engineering, and Mathematics) fields, and women may face hostile work environments in male-dominated industries, leading to higher attrition rates ([Schieder & Gould, 2016](https://www.epi.org/publication/womens-work-and-the-gender-pay-gap/); [Weyrauch, Sheppard, & Castle, 2019](https://www.inhersight.com/blog/occupational-sorting-does-job-choice-affect-the-gender-pay-gap)).

| Factor                          | Impact on Gender Pay Gap                           |
|--------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------|
| Occupational segregation        | Significant; women clustered in lower-paid jobs |
| Societal norms and stereotypes | Influence career aspirations and choices         |
| Workplace culture              | Hostility in male-dominated fields leads to attrition |

### 2. The Motherhood Penalty

One of the most substantial contributors to the gender pay gap is the "motherhood penalty." Mothers experience wage penalties, reduced hiring prospects, lower starting salaries, and diminished perceptions of competence and commitment compared to childless women and men with children ([Correll, Benard, & Paik, 2007](https://gender.stanford.edu/news-publications/publications/getting-job-there-motherhood-penalty); [Eberhard, 2014](https://medium.com/@kristin.eberhard/why-do-women-get-paid-less-than-men-3e9f4e9e1b3b)).

In contrast, fathers often receive a "fatherhood premium," being perceived as more committed and competent, which can lead to higher salaries and promotion opportunities ([Baranowska & Matysiak, 2022](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/357857618_Family_Size_and_Men’s_Labor_Market_Outcomes_Do_Social_Beliefs_About_Men’s_Roles_in_the_Family_Matter)).

| Parental Status | Perception of Commitment | Impact on Salary and Promotion          |
|-----------------|--------------------------|---------------------------------------|
| Mothers         | Less competent, less committed | Lower starting salaries, fewer promotions |
| Fathers         | More competent, more committed | Higher salaries, promotion advantages  |
| Childless Women | Higher competence perception | Higher salaries than mothers            |

### 3. Discrimination and Bias

Experimental studies reveal that discrimination plays a direct role in the pay gap. For instance, identical resumes with female names receive lower competence ratings and salary offers than those with male names ([Correll et al., 2007](https://gender.stanford.edu/news-publications/publications/getting-job-there-motherhood-penalty)). Moreover, mothers face harsher judgments and are penalized in hiring and salary decisions, while fathers do not ([Cheung et al., 2022](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10869-021-09782-0)).

Discrimination also manifests subtly through stereotypes that women are less committed or less capable, especially when balancing work and family responsibilities ([Cuddy, Fiske, & Glick, 2004](https://psycnet.apa.org/record/2004-15381-002)).

### 4. Work Hours, Flexibility, and Career Interruptions

Women, particularly mothers, are more likely to reduce working hours or take career breaks to fulfill caregiving responsibilities. These interruptions lead to loss of experience, slower career progression, and lower accumulated human capital, all of which depress wages over time ([Bolotnyy & Emanuel, 2018](https://www.nber.org/papers/w24736)).

Furthermore, women often accept less demanding jobs or part-time roles to accommodate family needs, which tend to be lower paid and offer fewer advancement opportunities ([Schieder & Gould, 2016](https://www.epi.org/publication/womens-work-and-the-gender-pay-gap/)).

### 5. Pay Gaps Within Occupations

Even within the same occupations, women earn less than men. This within-occupation pay gap suggests that factors beyond job type contribute to wage disparities. For example, female teachers earn less than male teachers, and female physicians earn less than male physicians with similar qualifications ([Schieder & Gould, 2016](https://www.epi.org/publication/womens-work-and-the-gender-pay-gap/)).

---

## Quantifying the Contributions to the Gender Pay Gap

Estimates vary, but research suggests the gender pay gap can be decomposed approximately as follows:

| Factor                         | Estimated Contribution to Pay Gap (%) | Explanation                                        |
|--------------------------------|--------------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------|
| Occupational sorting            | 25–45                               | Women concentrated in lower-paying fields        |
| Time off for caregiving         | 10–16                               | Career breaks and reduced hours                   |
| Direct discrimination           | 25–35                               | Bias in hiring, pay, and promotion decisions     |
| Unexplained residual (other factors) | ~10–20                          | Includes negotiation differences, cultural norms |

This breakdown highlights that discrimination and motherhood penalties are substantial contributors, not fully explained by job choice or experience differences ([Eberhard, 2014](https://medium.com/@kristin.eberhard/why-do-women-get-paid-less-than-men-3e9f4e9e1b3b); [Schieder & Gould, 2016](https://www.epi.org/publication/womens-work-and-the-gender-pay-gap/)).

